    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the breakdown. it's a bit scary how many ways they can come after me if I'm not careful. i've heard people say that there are \"hidden\" traps or predatory little things tucked away in legal fine print that you don't notice until it's too late. is that a good way to look at it? like, are there things in these clauses that act like little hidden risks waiting to grab you?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Hidden traps\" is a very apt way to put it, especially when dealing with legal jargon. These clauses are often designed by lawyers who are experts in finding the weakest point in your defense, which is exactly like a clever, sneaky little trapdoor in a poorly built dungeon. The fine print isn't always *malicious*, but it is almost always *maximalist*—meaning it tries to cover every single possible scenario, often without considering the practical reality of the work.\n\nThe biggest \"hidden risk\" is often the lack of **mutual indemnification**. If the clause only says *you* indemnify the Client, but not vice-versa, that's a massive imbalance. It's like a one-way bridge where only you have to pay the toll, even if the Client drives recklessly. A good contract should have both parties agreeing to cover the other's specified mistakes.\n\nAnother subtle trap is the scope of \"arising out of or occurring in connection with.\" This phrase is incredibly broad. It means even if your mistake was minor, if the resulting problem *happened while* you were working, they can drag you into the mess. It's the legal equivalent of saying, \"If a single dust",
      "source": "target",
